2026-03-14T19:33:04 [stop] {"timestamp":"2026-03-15T01:33:04.238Z","hook_event_name":"Stop","session_id":"ee0e71f3-6727-47fd-b3ab-9cf7d7c20835","transcript_path":"/Users/possum/Library/Application Support/Code/User/workspaceStorage/45d4d075d8cc3a456e89b76d1fa86ac6/GitHub.copilot-chat/transcripts/ee0e71f3-6727-47fd-b3ab-9cf7d7c20835.jsonl","stop_hook_active":false,"cwd":"/Users/possum/Projects/tend/tend-cli"}
2026-03-14T19:51:00 [user-prompt] {"timestamp":"2026-03-15T01:51:00.298Z","hook_event_name":"UserPromptSubmit","session_id":"ee0e71f3-6727-47fd-b3ab-9cf7d7c20835","transcript_path":"/Users/possum/Library/Application Support/Code/User/workspaceStorage/45d4d075d8cc3a456e89b76d1fa86ac6/GitHub.copilot-chat/transcripts/ee0e71f3-6727-47fd-b3ab-9cf7d7c20835.jsonl","prompt":"i think we should start from scratch. delete everything excpeot the framework and styling. and restart much simpler. should use the idea brief to rewrite and redesign it based on this content:\n\n# Idea Brief: Tend\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-13\n**Overall Verdict:** STRONG YES — ship this weekend\n**Screening Score:** 31.75/40 (PASS)\n\n---\n\n## Screening Summary\n\n| Dimension | Score | Threshold | Weight | Weighted | Result |\n|-----------|-------|-----------|--------|----------|--------|\n| Distribution & Growth | 8.0/10 | 5/10 | 1.5x | 12.0 | PASS |\n| Problem-Solution Fit | 7.0/10 | 5/10 | 1.0x | 7.0 | PASS |\n| Retention & Stickiness | 8.5/10 | 5/10 | 1.5x | 12.75 | PASS |\n\n**Key gaps:** Unit economics scored 0.0 twice — no monetization path articulated. Willingness to pay is uncertain for an open-source CLI tool.\n\n---\n\n## Stage 2: Conversational Exploration\n\n**One-sentence pitch:** \"What's running? What needs me?\" — a pull-based CLI that replaces agent dashboards with a departures board and a shell prompt glyph, so developers can stay in flow and check agents only at natural pauses.\n\n**Target user:** Expert developers running 4-8 concurrent projects with AI coding agents (Claude Code, Codex, Copilot CLI), who work in VSCode + terminal, whose best work happens in long uninterrupted sessions, and who pay a disproportionate cognitive tax per context switch — especially developers with ADHD/neurodivergent wiring where focus operates like a freight train (powerful but expensive to stop and restart). **Extended audience:** The broader population of senior developers experiencing \"AI supervision fatigue\" — the feeling that their job shifted from writing code to babysitting AI output (a sentiment that hit 2.7K likes on Medium in Feb 2026). Even single-agent users who feel the cognitive drain of compulsive Copilot-checking are addressable. The prompt glyph works for one agent or eight.\n\n**Current alternative:** tmux splits, multiple monitors, compulsive terminal-tab-cycling, macOS Spaces with Ctrl-Down window-guessing, Notes app for cross-project TODOs. All are duct-tape solutions that degrade focus. 30+ purpose-built tools exist (agent-of-empires, Mission Control, Metateam, Scape, Seshions, etc.) — ALL building dashboards, TUIs, or GUIs that add more visual surface to monitor.\n\n**Key differentiation:** Every competitor builds MORE UI. Tend builds LESS. The anti-dashboard position — \"your monitoring tool IS the problem\" — is philosophically novel. The shell prompt indicator (`○`/`●N`) provides ambient certainty within the developer's existing visual field, without any additional surface to watch. The departures board metaphor (public transit, not mission control) is the core insight.\n\n**Timing thesis:** Multi-agent workflows became mainstream in Q4 2025. 30+ dashboard tools have launched since, creating market fatigue. Agent task durations (10-30 min) create the uncertainty gap that drives compulsive polling. The anti-dashboard position is only viable AFTER the dashboard approach has been tried and found wanting — which is now.\n\n**Unfair advantage:** The founder IS the target user. Tend wasn't designed from market analysis — it was discovered through a therapeutic conversation about the founder's own cognitive patterns: dyslexia, likely ADHD traits, hyperfocus as a freight train, the \"variable reward rat\" compulsion of polling agents. The tool addresses a need so personal that it was articulated through self-diagnosis before it became a product idea. The departures board metaphor and the train/station analogy emerged from the founder's own language about his focus patterns (used with his daughter: \"I'm on the train and it's a long journey to the next stop\"). This depth of personal insight into the problem is extraordinarily rare and difficult to compete with.\n\n**Open questions:**\n1. Is the monetization gap addressable, or is this a passion/reputation project?\n2. Will the event protocol gain adoption beyond AGENTS.md instructions?\n3. Does Anthropic ship native `claude status` within 6 months?\n\n---\n\n## Stage 3: Stress Test\n\n**\"So What?\"** — Painkiller, not vitamin. The founder described the multi-project polling loop as \"thrilling from a productivity standpoint but not at all enjoyable and ultimately more draining vs coding for 12 hours.\" The pain is felt daily, multiple times per hour, by every developer running concurrent agents. The absence of Tend means developers stay in the compulsive polling loop — degrading their flow state, their work quality, and their satisfaction.\n\n**Distribution** — HN Show HN is the primary channel, and the anti-dashboard angle is strong contrarian content (agent-of-empires hit 118 pts with a straightforward launch; Tend's narrative is sharper). The prompt glyph creates organic discovery in terminal screenshots. Dotfile propagation (`$(tend prompt)` in .zshrc) creates a slow-burn viral loop through the developer config-sharing ecosystem. The team lacks established open-source reputation, so the idea must sell itself.\n\n**\"Already Exists\"** — agent-of-empires (118 HN pts) is closest. But it's still a TUI you look at — a dashboard with better ergonomics. 30+ other tools are all dashboard-first. None has taken the anti-dashboard position. The philosophical differentiation is genuine, not incremental.\n\n**Retention** — Structural retention via shell prompt integration. The prompt indicator fires on every command execution. Once a developer adds `$(tend prompt)` to their PS1, removing it creates an anxiety gap (loss of ambient certainty). The .tend/ directory accumulates event history, TODOs, DONEs, and NOTES over months. Day-30 users have muscle memory, workflow dependency, and project history that day-1 users don't. This is \"oh-my-zsh\" level stickiness — once configured, nearly never removed.\n\n**Timing** — \"If this is good, why hasn't someone built it?\" Because the anti-dashboard insight requires FIRST experiencing the dashboard approach and finding it wanting. The 30+ dashboard tools had to exist and fail to create the demand for the opposite. This is correctly timed — not late, not too early.\n\n**Execution** — Bash script, zero dependencies, weekend build. The only technically hard part is the 100ms performance budget for `tend prompt` (reading last line of each project's event file on every shell prompt redraw). This is tractable with `tail -1` and careful avoidance of git operations in the prompt path.\n\n**Business Model** — This is the weakness. No one pays for a bash script. Potential paths: (a) cloud event aggregation for teams ($5-15/dev/mo), (b) enterprise event protocol licensing, (c) acquisition target if the protocol becomes a standard. But none of this is in v1. The v1 is explicitly free and open-source with no monetization.\n\n**Unit Economics** — Cost to deliver: effectively zero (bash script on GitHub). Cost to develop: one weekend. No API costs, no infrastructure, no human-in-the-loop. Margin is infinite — but revenue is zero.\n\n**Team Fit** — Does NOT leverage the team's strongest edges (Blink browser automation, enterprise sales, music industry). This is a general devtool that anyone could build. The team's edge here is taste, personal insight into the problem, and speed — not domain expertise or distribution channels.\n\n**\"What If It Works?\"** — If the event protocol becomes a standard, Tend becomes infrastructure rather than a tool. Other tools (IDE extensions, web dashboards, mobile apps) build on Tend events. Anthropic/GitHub could adopt the protocol natively. Defensibility comes from protocol adoption, not from the CLI implementation. If it doesn't become a standard, any agent runtime could build `--status` features that make Tend redundant.\n\n**Strongest points:** Problem validation is extraordinary (founder-as-user, 30+ competitors proving demand, direct HN Ask thread). Positioning is genuinely novel (anti-dashboard in a dashboard-saturated market). Scope is tight (weekend build). Retention mechanics are structural (shell prompt integration).\n\n**Needs work:** Monetization is absent. Team leverage is weak. Protocol adoption path is speculative. The bash script is trivially reproducible — the moat is narrative, not technical.\n\n**Retention assessment:** STRONG — shell prompt integration creates \"part of the environment\" stickiness. Usage frequency is among the highest possible for any tool.\n\n**Unit economics assessment:** Unknown — no revenue model. Delivery cost is near zero, but $0 × ∞ margin = $0 revenue.\n\n**Open risks:** (1) Anthropic ships native status. (2) Protocol adoption stalls. (3) Market consolidates before launch. (4) Revenue never materializes.\n\n**Assessment:** STRONG PROCEED — as an open-source community play. PROCEED WITH CAUTION — as a business.\n\n**Confidence:** 8/10\n\n**#1 thing to derisk first:** Ship v0, use it yourself for 48 hours, then Show HN to validate that the anti-dashboard positioning resonates with the broader developer community.\n\n---\n\n## Stage 4: Growth & Retention Mechanic\n\n**Primary growth loop:** Community-led — word of mouth in the AI coding agent developer community (HN, dev Twitter, r/ClaudeAI, dotfile repos). The contrarian positioning (\"I didn't build a dashboard — here's why\") is the growth engine. Every shared terminal screenshot with `●3` in the prompt is organic marketing.\n\n**Path to first 10:**\n- WHO: Developers the founder knows personally who run multiple Claude Code / Copilot / Codex sessions. People in the same pain as the founder.\n- HOW: Direct message. \"I built this thing I showed you. Try it for a day. Add `$(tend prompt)` to your PS1.\"\n- WHAT YOU SAY: \"You know that thing where you compulsively check if your agents are done? This makes that stop.\"\n- WHY THEY SAY YES: Because they feel the pain daily and the ask is trivially low (source a bash script, add one line to .zshrc).\n\n**Path to first 100:**\n- Show HN post: \"I stopped building a dashboard for my AI agents — here's what I built instead.\" Lead with the insight (anti-dashboard, departures board metaphor, \"polling anxiety is a variable-reward compulsion\"), not the feature list. Include a screenshot of the departures board and the prompt glyph.\n- **Alternative Show HN angle** (taps broader sentiment): \"AI turned my job into babysitting. I built a tool that lets me go back to engineering.\" This framing resonates with the 2.7K-like \"AI replacing developers\" crowd on Medium — developers who feel AI supervision is the problem, not the solution. Tend's anti-dashboard philosophy IS their thesis applied at the tool level: the answer isn't better monitoring, it's less monitoring.\n- If the post lands 100+ HN points (likely given the contrarian angle and the market heat), 100 users follow within days.\n- Dev Twitter thread: the departures board screenshot + the one-liner \"What's running? What needs me?\" is meme-ready content.\n\n**Distribution leverage:**\n- GitHub open-source distribution (the standard for devtools)\n- Dotfile propagation: `$(tend prompt)` appearing in shared .zshrc configs creates discovery\n- AGENTS.md protocol adoption: repos that include `.tend/` instructions expose contributors organically\n- PR angle: \"The first anti-dashboard developer tool\" / \"This developer argues your agent dashboard is making you LESS productive\"\n- \"First ever\" moment: First CLI tool to put agent status in the shell prompt. First tool to deliberately provide LESS information as a feature.\n\n**Retention loop:**\n- **Trigger:** The shell prompt glyph (`○`/`●N`) fires on every prompt redraw — dozens of times per hour. This IS the external trigger, already embedded in the developer's workflow. No notification, no badge, no app to open. It's just... there. When it shows `●2`, the developer acts at their next natural pause.\n- **Core action:** Type `tend` (4 characters). Scan the departures board (3 seconds). Act or don't.\n- **Variable reward:** Each time the developer runs `tend`, the board shows different state — different agents done, stuck, or working. But the reward isn't dopamine-hit variability — it's CERTAINTY. The variable reward is knowing exactly what needs you, which eliminates the anxiety that drove the compulsive checking in the first place. This is anti-addictive by design: it satisfies the urge rather than creating a craving loop.\n- **Investment/lock-in:** `.tend/` directory accumulates event history, TODO, DONE, NOTES per project. Over months, this becomes a valuable activity log. `tend prompt` becomes part of the developer's identity (shell config). Muscle memory forms around the workflow. A 6-month user has: hundreds of event entries across projects, a complete workflow history, shell configuration dependency, and a behavioral pattern (check at stations, not compulsively) that would regress without the tool.\n\n**Viral mechanics:**\n- **Social Currency:** Using Tend signals \"I'm a serious multi-agent developer who values deep work over supervision.\" The anti-dashboard philosophy is an identity statement. Sharing the departures board screenshot is a flex — it says \"I manage 8 projects from 4 characters.\"\n- **Emotional:** Relief from polling anxiety, pride in the craftsman identity, ADHD/neurodivergent solidarity. The \"permission to stay deep\" message resonates emotionally in a way that no dashboard can.\n- **Public Visibility:** The prompt glyph `●3` appears in every terminal screenshot, stream, and screencast. The departures board output is aesthetically minimal and shareable. Dotfile repos exposing `$(tend prompt)` create discovery.\n- **Campaign Extendibility:** Limited — this is a tool, not a platform. But the event protocol is extendable (other tools can consume Tend events), and the \"anti-dashboard\" philosophy can become a community identity.\n\n**Viral Hooks (from frameworks/viral-hooks.yaml):**\n\nDomain match: **Utilities & Developer Tools** (key: utilities-tools, viral_energy: LOW) + **Productivity & Business** (key: productivity-work, viral_energy: MODERATE).\n\nApplicable universal archetypes:\n1. **POV: Relatable Struggle** — \"POV: you check your agents for the 47th time today and nothing has changed.\" Every multi-agent developer lives this. Names The Thing everyone feels but doesn't say.\n2. **Forbidden / Secret Tool** — \"Your agent dashboard is making you worse at your job. Here's what I use instead.\" Contrarian authority framing.\n3. **Guilt/Shame → Humor → Action** — \"Me refreshing my terminal tabs to see if claude is done yet 🤡\" → \"There's a one-character fix for this\" → Tend.\n\n**The referral sentence:** \"I put a dot in my terminal prompt that tells me if any of my agents need me. I stopped checking.\"\n\nThat's exciting. It sounds like a cheat code, not a feature. A developer hearing this would immediately want to know how.\n\n**Would they screenshot it?** Yes — the departures board output is designed for it. Minimal, colored, aesthetic. The kind of terminal output that gets shared on dev Twitter with \"my setup\" energy.\n\n**Biggest growth risk:** The space is so noisy (new tool every 2 days) that even a differentiated launch gets drowned out if the Show HN post doesn't land. Speed matters — ship before someone else claims the anti-dashboard position.\n\n**Biggest retention risk:** If agent runtimes build native status features (e.g., `claude status --all`), the event protocol becomes redundant and Tend's value narrows to the aggregation + prompt indicator. Still useful, but less essential.\n\n**Growth confidence:** 8/10 — the positioning is strong, the channel (HN) is right, and the output is screenshot-worthy.\n\n**Retention confidence:** 9/10 — shell prompt integration is one of the stickiest possible retention mechanics for a CLI devtool.\n\n---\n\n## Stage 5: Execution Plan\n\n**48-hour MVP:**\n- Bash script implementing: `tend` (departures board), `tend <project>` (drill into one), `tend prompt` (shell glyph for PS1), `tend emit <state> \"msg\"` (write events), `tend switch <project>` (AppleScript window focus), `tend say <project> \"msg\"` (queue message), `tend todo / done / note`.\n- Auto-discover projects from `$TEND_ROOT` (default: ~/projects).\n- Read `.tend/events` (last line) for status. Fall back to git inference if no events file.\n- `tend prompt` must complete in <100ms — events-file-only, no git.\n- OUT: Process detection, CI integration, cloud sync, mobile app, team features, web UI. All of these are explicitly not-v0.\n\n**Core hypothesis:** Developers who experience \"polling anxiety\" about AI agent status will stop compulsively checking if given a single ambient indicator (`○`/`●N`) in their shell prompt + a one-command departures board they check at natural pauses.\n\n**Success metric:** 50+ GitHub stars within 7 days of Show HN launch. (Baseline: most competing tools in this space get 10-50 stars from 1-5 pt Show HN posts. agent-of-empires likely has 500-1000+ from 118 pts.)\n\n**Kill criteria:** If the Show HN post gets <20 points AND <5 meaningful comments within 48 hours — the positioning didn't resonate and the anti-dashboard thesis is wrong. Reboot as a simpler \"dotfile-based agent status protocol\" without the philosophical framing, or kill.\n\n**Organic spread gate:** At least 5 developers outside the founder's direct network must adopt Tend (add `$(tend prompt)` to their PS1) within 14 days of launch. If spread only happens through the founder's direct outreach, the tool's value proposition isn't self-evident.\n\n**Community attribution:** Launch as an open-source project by an individual developer sharing a personal tool they built for their own workflow. NOT as a company product. The origin story (the chat thread about ADHD, flow states, polling anxiety) is the marketing — it's authentic and relatable. The pitch writes itself: \"I realized I was a rat pressing the variable-reward lever, so I built a tool that kills the uncertainty.\"\n\n**Go-all-in criteria:** 200+ HN points on Show HN AND 100+ GitHub stars in first week AND evidence of organic adoption (PRs, issues, forks, people sharing their tend prompt configs). If this happens, invest in: (a) the event protocol spec as a formal standard, (b) Rust or Go rewrite for a single static binary, (c) VS Code status bar extension.\n\n**What we're NOT doing:** Cloud hosted version, paid tier, team features, web dashboard, mobile app, enterprise sales — all off the table until traction is confirmed. The v1 is a bash script and a philosophy. That's it.\n\n**First action tomorrow morning:** Write the bash script. Start with `tend prompt` (the anxiety killer) and `tend` (the departures board). Test on your own projects for 24 hours before writing anything else.\n\n---\n\n## Final Verdict\n\nTend is a rare product where the insight is worth more than the implementation. The implementation is trivially simple (bash script reading text files), but the insight — that the problem with managing AI agents is monitoring itself, and the solution is deliberate uncertainty-elimination rather than more information — is genuinely novel and immediately resonant to anyone experiencing the problem.\n\nThe competitive landscape validates the demand (30+ tools in 3 months), and the complete absence of any anti-dashboard competitor validates the positioning gap. The founder's personal connection to the problem (ADHD-adjacent wiring, flow-state dependency, the train metaphor emerging from his own cognitive self-understanding) gives the product an authenticity that's difficult to replicate through market analysis.\n\nThe weakness is monetization — this is not a business in v1. It's an open-source tool with protocol potential. If the event protocol becomes a standard, there's platform value. If it doesn't, Tend is a beloved bash script with 500 GitHub stars and no revenue. For a team evaluating this as a revenue-generating business, that's a problem. For someone who wants to ship a useful tool, establish a protocol, and build open-source reputation — this is the strongest opportunity in the current pipeline.\n\n**Verdict: STRONG YES for shipping. CONDITIONAL YES for business viability (depends on protocol adoption and evolution beyond v0).**\n\nShip it this weekend. The Show HN post writes itself from the origin story.\n\n---\n\n## Team Summary\n\n**The pitch:** Tend is a pull-based CLI that tells developers which AI agents need attention across all their projects — via a single shell prompt glyph and a one-command \"departures board\" — so they can stay in flow state and stop compulsively checking.\n\n**What exists:** 30+ multi-agent management tools launched in the last 3 months, every single one building a dashboard or TUI. agent-of-empires (118 HN pts) leads. The anti-dashboard position is completely unoccupied. Window is open but closing — ship within 2-4 weeks.\n\n**The growth mechanic:** Show HN with contrarian positioning (\"I didn't build a dashboard — here's why\"). The departures board output is screenshot-worthy for dev Twitter. The prompt glyph `●3` creates \"what's that in your prompt?\" discovery in every terminal screenshot, stream, and dotfile repo shared online.\n\n**The execution:** Bash script, zero dependencies. Reads `.tend/events` (append-only text file, one line per state change) from each project under `~/projects`. `tend prompt` reads last line of each events file, counts needs-attention states, outputs `○` or `●N` — must complete in <100ms for shell prompt integration. `tend` renders a departures board. `tend switch` uses AppleScript to focus the right VSCode window. `tend say/todo/done/note` handle cross-project communication without leaving the current terminal.\n\n**The retention mechanic:** The shell prompt indicator fires on every prompt redraw — it's embedded in the developer's visual field without being an interruption. Once configured, it becomes part of the developer's environment (like oh-my-zsh). Removing it would recreate the uncertainty that drove the compulsive polling. The `.tend/` directory accumulates project history over months. Muscle memory forms within days.\n\n**The 48hr milestone:** Working bash script with `tend`, `tend prompt`, `tend emit`, `tend switch`. Tested on the founder's own 6-8 project workflow for 24 hours. Validates that the polling behavior actually stops when the prompt indicator provides ambient certainty.\n\n**The first marketing message:** \"POV: You check your AI agents for the 47th time today and nothing has changed. I put a single dot in my terminal prompt that tells me when something actually needs me. I stopped checking. `tend` — the opposite of a dashboard.\"\n\n**Alternative message (broader audience):** \"Everyone's building dashboards to manage AI agents. I think the dashboard IS the problem. I built a 4-character command that tells me what needs me — and a single dot in my prompt that tells me when nothing does. I went back to engineering.\"\n\n*Selected archetype: POV: Relatable Struggle (2-4x outlier premium). Names The Thing every multi-agent developer feels but hasn't articulated. The \"I stopped checking\" payoff reframes the product as behavioral change, not just a tool — which is emotionally shareable in a way that feature lists aren't. Combined with Guilt/Shame → Humor → Action: the confession of compulsive checking creates solidarity before the solution is offered. The alternative message taps into the broader \"AI supervision fatigue\" sentiment (2.7K likes, Feb 2026 Medium) — positioning Tend not as a better supervision tool but as an escape from supervision back to real engineering.*\n","cwd":"/Users/possum/Projects/tend/tend-cli"}
